//Maximum Depth of Binary Tree
//Given the root of a binary tree, return its maximum depth.
//A binary tree's maximum depth is the number of nodes along the longest path from the root node down to the farthest leaf node.
//Example 1:
//Input: root = [3,9,20,null,null,15,7]
//Output: 3
//Example 2:
//Input: root = [1,null,2]
//Output: 2

Brute Force Approach -> (Level Order Traversal / BFS)

class Solution {
public:
    int maxDepth(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root == nullptr) {
            return 0;
        }
        queue<TreeNode*> q;
        q.push(root);
        int depth = 0;
        while(!q.empty()) {
            int size = q.size();
            for(int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
                TreeNode* node = q.front();
                q.pop();
                if(node->left) {
                    q.push(node->left);
                }
                if(node->right) {
                    q.push(node->right);
                }
            }
            depth++;
        }
        return depth;
    }
};


Intuition ->

Traverse the tree level by level.
Each time we finish processing one level, increase the depth by 1.
When all levels are processed, the depth variable contains the maximum depth.

Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes in the tree
Reason:
Every node is visited exactly once.

Space Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes in the tree
Reason:
The queue may store an entire level of the tree.



Optimal Approach -> (Recursive DFS)

class Solution {
public:
    int maxDepth(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root == nullptr) {
            return 0;
        }

        return 1 + max(maxDepth(root->left),
                       maxDepth(root->right));
    }
};

Intuition ->

For every node:
Depth =
1 + maximum(depth of left subtree,
            depth of right subtree)
The extra 1 counts the current node.

Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = number of nodes in the tree
Reason:
Every node is visited exactly once.

Space Complexity -> O(h)
where:
h = height of the tree
Reason:
Recursive call stack stores at most h function calls at one time.

Dry Run of Optimal Approach ->

Input:
        3
       / \
      9   20
         /  \
        15   7
Step 1
At node 9:
left depth = 0
right depth = 0
depth = 1 + max(0,0)
      = 1
Returns:
1

Step 2
At node 15:
left depth = 0
right depth = 0
depth = 1 + max(0,0)
      = 1
Returns:
1

Step 3
At node 7:
left depth = 0
right depth = 0
depth = 1 + max(0,0)
      = 1
Returns:
1

Step 4
At node 20:
left depth = 1
right depth = 1
depth = 1 + max(1,1)
      = 2
Returns:
2

Step 5
At node 3:
left depth = 1
right depth = 2
depth = 1 + max(1,2)
      = 3
Returns:
3

Final Answer:
3

